    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. so with CIF, if something happens to the cargo while it's still in transit on the ocean, the seller is the one who has to deal with the insurance claim because they're the ones who arranged it, right? even though the risk technically transferred earlier? i'm trying to figure out the exact moment the maritime risk shifts.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This is a common point of confusion, as the transfer of risk and the handling of insurance claims can differ. Under CIF, the *risk* generally transfers to you when the goods pass the ship's rail in Ningbo, similar to FOB. However, since the seller purchased the insurance, they are typically the ones who initiate the claim process with the carrier or insurer, even if you are the ultimate insured party. It's best to review the specific insurance policy details to confirm who must act as the claimant.",
      "source": "target",
